It is an event, which implies: It has intrinsic symbolism to different parties; It knows a timeframe and deadlines; It has crowds, however small, and generally VIPs present; It’s not just the event itself, but extends to people coming and going to and from the event (if something goes wrong); and It attracts media attention. 

Major event organization means multiple stakeholders, e.g.: Organizers 
Authorities 
Insurers 
Participants/Talent 
Public Media 
Vendors 
Sponsors 
Transport 

It is major (size/importance/profile), which implies:

It is of some size and may well be multi-venue; 
The site may well have a unique infrastructure unfamiliar to many; 
The event may well be of some duration (month-long World Cup); 
Most events will know multiple public-private partnership parties and dimensions, starting with safety and security; 
There are likely to be considerable funds at stake in terms of revenue, investment, and insurance. 

Major events are increasingly international, if not by design then at least in attendance. For organizers, this implies: 
Duty of Care responsibilities as an organizer and host; 
The national brand is at stake; 
One will have to account for and appropriately deal with multiple languages and cultures; 
and There is a significant travel/transport/hotel aspect. 


As important as those four fixed dimensions is a fifth, and that, for lack of a better term, is the “big variables” around major events that often impede both emergency and crisis planning. The big variables around major events are: Planning requirements will change over time and require the customi zed application of Good Practice. British top crowd dynamics expert Professor Keith Still put it to me thus in 2020: “Many people don’t realize the review requirement of risk and customized measures applies for each event. Too many, especially venue shows and annual repeats, are handled by rote and in a compliance check-off fashion”; Each event venue, city and country has its constraints (be it the size of the budget or the number of law enforcement); Threats to major events differ and evolve, and there will be multiple ones (not just drunk fans, terrorists, mediocre safety inspectors, absent volunteers or poor WiFi infrastructure); Depending on what happens, multiple command centers are likely to overlap on response duties. Remember, events are temporary and have to co-exist and align with the fixed longterm area crisis ecosystem in place around them. Bear in mind too that the increase in COVID-19 era hybrid events combining live and online may prove a CM complicator for even small, closed events.

crises have seven characteristics, each offering a context for managing them. These are they: 
1. Pose sudden, urgent major challenges; 
2. Contain a degree of novelty to you; 
3. Require top-tier engagement; 
4. Disrupt regular routines; 
5. Disturb stakeholders; 
6. Create friction; and 
7. Have a tail.

‘Have a tail’ means that in spite of hard efforts to achieve a clear-cut endpoint and declarations they are over, a lot of crises drag on in some form. A tainted reputation, an investigation, regulatory scrutiny, lawsuits, restructuring requirements: all too often part of a crisis’s aftermath.

A Code Black is not for asking questions, waffling and wondering. It’s for organizing and executing fast, pre-set actions by professionals to get a few basic things done within a very short timespan. And once the pieces are in place, going from there. In planning, a Code Black usually prompts a series of pre-determined actions to do three things very rapidly: 
1. Alert people 
2. Rapidly boost response capabilities 
3. Rapidly reduce key vulnerabilities

Code Black-type codes for crisis preparedness often encompass steps like: 
1. Boosting staff numbers in an organization’s or a facility’s main Operations Center according to an Emergency Operations or “Crash Plan”; 
2. Calling up the primary crisis team; 
3. Placing the back-up crisis team on stand-by; 
4. Prepping the alternate crisis room site (as well); 
5. Calling up designated Communications and IT staff to support emergency and possible crisis operations; 
6. Activating messaging protocols to inform predesignated key stakeholders that your crisis preparedness posture has just been increased to “Level One”; and
7. Initiating call-ups of select outside resources and issue experts to enable them to be ready to assist if required.

# The Dichotomy of Leadership

A good leader must be:

• confident but not cocky;

• courageous but not foolhardy;

• competitive but a gracious loser;

• attentive to details but not obsessed by them;

• strong but have endurance;

• a leader and follower;

• humble not passive;

• aggressive not overbearing;

• quiet not silent;

• calm but not robotic, logical but not devoid of emotions;

• close with the troops but not so close that one becomes more important than another or more important than the good of the team; not so close that they forget who is in charge.

• able to execute Extreme Ownership, while exercising Decentralized Command.

_A good leader has nothing to prove, but everything to prove._

Willink, Jocko; Babin, Leif. Extreme Ownership (pp. 277-278). St. Martin's Publishing Group. Kindle Edition.
